    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="240"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860C.01/6–345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Truman</persName> to the
                        British Prime Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Churchill</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-06">June 6,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>58. Thank you for your encouraging message no. 67<note n="83" xml:id="d240fn83"
                        >Dated June 2, <ref target="#pg_317">p. 317</ref>.</note> expressing your
                    concurrence with the efforts Harry Hopkins has made in Moscow to get on with the
                    Polish business.</p>
                <p>I am repeating in my next message<note n="84" xml:id="d240fn84">President
                        Truman’s message No. 59 to Prime Minister Churchill, dated June 6, 1945 (not
                        printed), quoted President Truman’s message No. 283, June 5, to Mr. Hopkins,
                            <ref target="#pg_326">p. 326</ref>.</note> my reply to Harry Hopkins’
                    latest communications in regard to this matter. I sincerely hope that <pb
                        facs="0340" n="328" xml:id="pg_328"/> you concur in my suggestions. I would
                    appreciate receiving any comments you may care to make.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
